{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01EdXLNDmYiJztAUnREDWtgr","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Workflows\n     2→\n     3→Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4→\n     5→## Workflow Locations\n     6→\n     7→Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the `host { }` block:\n     8→\n     9→**Container workflows** — The default. Run inside a Docker container via `cloche-agent`.\n    10→Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the standard workflows for coding\n    11→tasks.\n    12→\n    13→**Host workflows** — Declared by including a `host { }` block in the workflow definition.\n    14→Run on the host machine as the daemon process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or\n    15→`workflow` type. The `workflow` step type dispatches a container workflow run and waits\n    16→for it to complete. This is the extension point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17→\n    18→Any `.cloche` file can contain host workflows — they are not restricted to a specific\n    19→filename. A single file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon uses up to\n    20→three workflow phases for orchestration:\n    21→\n    22→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n    23→|-------|--------------|---------|\n    24→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n    25→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n    26→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n    27→\n    28→Additionally, a **`release-task`** host workflow may be defined. This is not part of the\n    29→automatic orchestration loop — it is invoked on demand (e.g. from the web dashboard) to\n    30→release a stale claimed task back to `open` status. Receives `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` for the\n    31→task to release.\n    32→\n    33→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\n    34→single-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n    35→\n    36→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n    37→object with the following fields:\n    38→\n    39→| Field | Required | Description |\n    40→|-------|----------|-------------|\n    41→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n    42→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n    43→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n    44→| `description` | no | Full description |\n    45→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n    46→\n    47→The daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\n    48→compatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\n    49→Tasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\n    50→reassignment.\n    51→\n    52→The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    53→file is a parse error.\n    54→\n    55→## Concepts\n    56→\n    57→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    58→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    59→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    60→| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    61→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    62→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    63→| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n    64→| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n    65→\n    66→## Step Types\n    67→\n    68→Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    69→\n    70→**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    71→to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    72→container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    73→\n    74→**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    75→any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    76→\n    77→**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    78→until it completes. Only available in host workflows (those with a `host { }` block).\n    79→\n    80→A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    81→parse error.\n    82→\n    83→## DSL Syntax\n    84→\n    85→```\n    86→workflow \"develop\" {\n    87→  container {\n    88→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    89→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n    90→  }\n    91→\n    92→  step implement {\n    93→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    94→    results = [success, fail]\n    95→  }\n    96→\n    97→  step test {\n    98→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    99→    results = [success, fail]\n   100→  }\n   101→\n   102→  step fix {\n   103→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   104→    max_attempts = \"3\"\n   105→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   106→  }\n   107→\n   108→  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n   109→  implement:success -> test\n   110→  implement:fail    -> abort\n   111→  test:success      -> done\n   112→  test:fail         -> fix\n   113→  fix:success       -> test\n   114→  fix:fail          -> abort\n   115→  fix:give-up       -> abort\n   116→}\n   117→```\n   118→\n   119→## Key Properties\n   120→\n   121→**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n   122→field makes it a script step.\n   123→\n   124→**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n   125→report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n   126→\n   127→**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n   128→existing ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n   129→Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n   130→\n   131→**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n   132→wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   133→\n   134→## Wire Output Mappings\n   135→\n   136→Wires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   137→them as environment variables into the target step:\n   138→\n   139→```\n   140→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   141→```\n   142→\n   143→The general form:\n   144→\n   145→```\n   146→FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   147→```\n   148→\n   149→Where `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   150→starting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   151→\n   152→| Expression | Meaning |\n   153→|---|---|\n   154→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   155→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   156→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   157→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   158→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   159→\n   160→If the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   161→structure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   162→value is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   163→\n   164→If two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   165→returns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   166→wires to different steps without conflict.\n   167→\n   168→## Workflow-Level Configuration Blocks\n   169→\n   170→Workflows support a configuration block at the workflow level to set defaults for all\n   171→steps. The block name depends on the workflow location:\n   172→\n   173→**`container {}`** — For container workflows. Sets container image, agent command, and\n   174→network allowlist.\n   175→\n   176→```\n   177→workflow \"develop\" {\n   178→  container {\n   179→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n   180→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   181→    agent_args = \"-p --dangerously-skip-permissions\"\n   182→  }\n   183→  ...\n   184→}\n   185→```\n   186→\n   187→Supported keys: `image`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`, `network_allow`.\n   188→\n   189→**`host {}`** — Declares a workflow as a host workflow. Can appear in any `.cloche` file.\n   190→Sets agent defaults for agent steps running on the host machine. An empty `host {}` block\n   191→(no keys) is valid and simply marks the workflow as host-side.\n   192→\n   193→```\n   194→workflow \"main\" {\n   195→  host {\n   196→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   197→  }\n   198→  ...\n   199→}\n   200→```\n   201→\n   202→Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   203→\n   204→Step-level `agent_command` and `agent_args` override workflow-level defaults. The\n   205→resolution order is: step-level > workflow-level block > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env\n   206→var > default `claude`.\n   207→\n   208→## Host Workflow Example\n   209→\n   210→A three-phase host workflow setup with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\n   211→workflows:\n   212→\n   213→```\n   214→# Host workflows — runs on the host machine\n   215→\n   216→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   217→  step fetch-tickets {\n   218→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   219→    results = [success, fail]\n   220→  }\n   221→\n   222→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   223→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   224→}\n   225→\n   226→workflow \"main\" {\n   227→  host {\n   228→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   229→  }\n   230→\n   231→  step prepare-prompt {\n   232→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   233→    results = [success, fail]\n   234→  }\n   235→\n   236→  step develop {\n   237→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   238→    results       = [success, fail]\n   239→  }\n   240→\n   241→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   242→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   243→  develop:success        -> done\n   244→  develop:fail           -> done\n   245→}\n   246→\n   247→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   248→  step push-for-review {\n   249→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   250→    results = [success, fail]\n   251→  }\n   252→\n   253→  push-for-review:success -> done\n   254→  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   255→}\n   256→```\n   257→\n   258→The daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\n   259→runs `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\n   260→The `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   261→The `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\n   262→The `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n   263→`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n   264→\n   265→## Execution Model\n   266→\n   267→**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   268→container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   269→wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   270→All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   271→\n   272→**Host workflows** (those with a `host { }` block) are parsed and executed by the daemon\n   273→on the host machine. Any `.cloche` file may contain host workflows; the daemon\n   274→orchestrates them in three phases (list-tasks → main → finalize). Script steps run via\n   275→`sh -c` with the\n   276→working directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\n   277→if the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\n   278→host-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\n   279→runs via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n   280→`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\n   281→points to the actual project directory.\n   282→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01YBDNVBTQUf847DxND28odt","session_id":"955b2dd5-cc52-456b-afc0-0035f6eae0d8","uuid":"079cfcda-51db-4b7e-ac3a-1d11458ef031"}
{"type":"system","subtype":"task_notification","task_id":"ac4310c5ac652c299","tool_use_id":"toolu_01YBDNVBTQUf847DxND28odt","status":"completed","output_file":"","summary":"Explore project structure","usage":{"total_tokens":69837,"tool_uses":37,"duration_ms":71131},"uuid":"30ff5e69-e8c6-46e9-bfd2-aa49bc4b7991","session_id":"955b2dd5-cc52-456b-afc0-0035f6eae0d8"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YBDNVBTQUf847DxND28odt","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have all the information needed. Let me compile a comprehensive report.\n\n## Comprehensive Project Structure Exploration Report\n\nBased on thorough examination of the Cloche codebase, here's the complete understanding of the project structure and how it works:\n\n---\n\n### **1. CLI Command Structure** (cmd/cloche/)\n\n**Main.go dispatcher pattern:**\n- The CLI has a simple switch-based dispatcher in `main()` that routes commands into two categories:\n  1. **Non-daemon commands** (init, health, get, set, tasks, workflow, project) - execute locally or via HTTP\n  2. **Daemon commands** (run, status, logs, poll, list, stop, delete, loop, shutdown) - require gRPC connection\n\n- **Key entry points:**\n  - `cmdRun()` - Initiates workflow execution (lines 156-214)\n  - `cmdStatus()`, `cmdLogs()`, `cmdList()` - Query daemon state\n  - `cmdWorkflow()` - List/render workflows\n  - `cmdProject()` - Display project info\n  - `cmdInit()` - Bootstrap new project\n  - `cmdGet()` / `cmdSet()` - Run context store access\n\n- **Version handling:**\n  - Single version file at `/workspace/internal/version/VERSION` (currently \"1.3.0\")\n  - Embedded via `//go:embed` in `version/version.go`\n  - CLI shows version warnings if daemon/agent versions differ\n\n- **Command discovery:**\n  - All help text stored in `/cmd/cloche/help.go` in a `subcommandHelp` map\n  - Supports `cloche <cmd> --help`, `cloche help <cmd>`, and top-level `cloche --help`\n\n---\n\n### **2. Workflow DSL Parser** (internal/dsl/)\n\n**Parser Architecture:**\n- **Lexer** (`lexer.go`) - Tokenizes input into tokens (IDENT, STRING, INT, ARROW, etc.)\n- **Token types** (`token.go`) - 13 token types (LBRACE, RBRACE, LBRACKET, LBRACKET, ARROW, COLON, DOT, etc.)\n- **Parser** (`parser.go`, 616 lines) - Recursive descent parser that builds domain.Workflow objects\n\n**Key Parser Functions:**\n- `Parse(input string)` - Single workflow parse with optional location hint\n- `ParseAll(input string)` - Multiple workflows in one file (returns map[string]*domain.Workflow)\n- `ParseForHost(input string)` - Explicitly host location\n- `ParseAllForHost(input string)` - Multiple host workflows\n- `ParseForContainer(input string)` - Container location\n\n**DSL Grammar (from parser):**\n```\nworkflow \"<name>\" {\n  step <name> {\n    prompt = file(\"...\")   OR   run = \"...\"   OR   workflow_name = \"...\"\n    results = [result1, result2, ...]\n    <config-key> = <value>\n  }\n  \n  <step>:<result> -> <target-step> [output-mappings]\n  collect all|any(step:result, ...) -> target\n  \n  host { ... }     # marks as host workflow\n  container { ... } # container-specific config\n}\n```\n\n**Step Type Inference** (lines 268-297):\n- `prompt` field → agent step\n- `run` field → script step\n- `workflow_name` field → workflow step (host-only)\n- Must have exactly one; validation error otherwise\n\n**Wiring & Output Mappings** (parseWire, lines 446-482):\n- Format: `from:result -> to [KEY = output.path]`\n- Output paths support:\n  - `output` - raw output\n  - `output.field.nested` - JSON field access\n  - `output[0]` - array indexing\n  - Mixed: `output.items[0].name`\n\n**Collect Conditions** (parseCollect, lines 557-615):\n- Syntax: `collect all|any(step:result, ...) -> target`\n- Merges multiple results before wiring to next step\n\n---\n\n### **3. Domain Types** (internal/domain/workflow.go)\n\n**Core Types:**\n\n```go\ntype Workflow struct {\n  Name      string                // Workflow identifier\n  Location  WorkflowLocation      // host or container\n  Steps     map[string]*Step\n  Wiring    []Wire                // Graph edges\n  Collects  []Collect             // Multi-condition merges\n  EntryStep string                // First step to execute\n  Config    map[string]string     // Workflow-level config\n}\n\ntype Step struct {\n  Name    string\n  Type    StepType              // agent, script, workflow\n  Results []string              // Declared outcomes\n  Config  map[string]string     // Step-specific config\n}\n\ntype Wire struct {\n  From      string\n  Result    string\n  To        string\n  OutputMap []OutputMapping      // Env var mappings\n}\n\ntype OutputMapping struct {\n  EnvVar string\n  Path   OutputPath\n}\n\ntype Collect struct {\n  Mode       CollectMode           // all or any\n  Conditions []WireCondition\n  To         string\n}\n```\n\n**Workflow Location (lines 22-33):**\n- `LocationContainer` - default, runs in Docker\n- `LocationHost` - has `host { }` block, runs on daemon machine\n\n**WorkflowLocation vs StepType:**\n- Location determined by `host { }` block presence\n- Host workflows can have agent/script/workflow steps\n- Container workflows can only have agent/script steps\n- `ValidateLocation()` enforces this (lines 231-242)\n\n**Validation (lines 145-229):**\n- `Validate()` - Core validation (entry exists, all results wired, no orphans, output mappings unique)\n- `ValidateLocation()` - Rejects workflow_name in container workflows\n- `ValidateConfig()` - Warns about unrecognized config keys\n\n---\n\n### **4. Config Parsing** (internal/config/config.go)\n\n**Config File Location:**\n- Per-project: `<projectDir>/.cloche/config.toml`\n- Global: `~/.config/cloche/config` (optional)\n- Format: TOML using `github.com/BurntSushi/toml`\n\n**Config Structure:**\n```go\ntype Config struct {\n  Active        bool\n  Daemon        DaemonConfig        // listen, http, image, db, runtime, agent_path, llm_command\n  Evolution     EvolutionConfig     // enabled, debounce_seconds, min_confidence, max_prompt_bullets\n  Orchestration OrchestrationConfig // concurrency, stagger_seconds, list_tasks_command, dedup_seconds, stop_on_error\n}\n```\n\n**Load Function (line 57-74):**\n- Returns defaults if file missing\n- Merges file values with defaults()\n- Defaults: concurrency=1, stagger=1.0s, evolution enabled, debounce=30s\n\n**Default Template** (cmd/cloche/init.go, lines 73-82):\n- Created by `cloche init`\n- Sets `active = false` (must be manually enabled)\n\n---\n\n### **5. Project Directory & .cloche Resolution** (cmd/cloche/)\n\n**Current Working Directory Pattern:**\n- All commands use `os.Getwd()` to get project directory\n- Workflow loading: `projectDir + \"/.cloche/\" + name + \".cloche\"`\n- Glob discovery: `filepath.Glob(filepath.Join(clocheDir, \"*.cloche\"))`\n\n**Key Functions:**\n- `loadWorkflow(projectDir, name)` - Load single workflow by name (workflow.go, lines 119-141)\n- `discoverWorkflows(projectDir)` - Scan all `.cloche` files, parse workflows (lines 51-74)\n- `listWorkflows(projectDir)` - Group by location (container/host)\n- `showWorkflow(projectDir, name)` - Render ASCII graph\n\n**Path Resolution in cmdRun (lines 192-203):**\n```go\ncwd, _ := os.Getwd()\n// Try to load workflow to extract image config\nif wf, err := loadWorkflow(cwd, workflow); err == nil && wf.Location == domain.LocationContainer {\n  image = wf.Config[\"container.image\"]\n}\n// Send projectDir and image to daemon\nresp, err := client.RunWorkflow(ctx, &pb.RunWorkflowRequest{\n  ProjectDir: cwd,\n  Image:      image,\n  ...\n})\n```\n\n**Command Pattern:**\n- `cloche workflow` → lists all workflows\n- `cloche workflow <name>` → renders specific workflow graph\n- `cloche workflow <name> -p <dir>` → looks in alternate project directory\n\n---\n\n### **6. Workflow File Examples**\n\n**Container Workflow** (/workspace/develop.cloche):\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  step implement { prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\"); results = [success, fail] }\n  step test { run = \"go test ./...\"; results = [success, fail] }\n  \n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail -> abort\n  test:success -> done\n  test:fail -> abort\n}\n```\n\n**Host Workflow** (cmd/cloche/init.go, lines 104-123):\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  step prepare-prompt { run = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"; results = [success, fail] }\n  step develop { workflow_name = \"develop\"; results = [success, fail] }\n  \n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  develop:success -> done\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### **7. Validation Logic**\n\n**Parse-Time Validation (workflow.go):**\n\n1. **Structure validation** (`Validate()`, line 145):\n   - Entry step exists and is defined\n   - All step results are wired (no dead results)\n   - All steps reachable from entry (no orphans)\n   - Output mappings don't duplicate env vars to same target\n\n2. **Location validation** (`ValidateLocation()`, line 231):\n   - Container workflows reject `workflow_name` steps\n   - Host workflows accept all step types\n\n3. **Config validation** (`ValidateConfig()`, line 259):\n   - Known keys: `prompt`, `run`, `max_attempts`, `timeout`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`, `results`, `feedback`, `workflow_name`, `prompt_step`\n   - Container-prefixed keys allowed: `container.*`\n   - Host-prefixed keys allowed: `host.*`\n   - Returns warnings for unknown keys (typo detection)\n\n**Parser Validation:**\n- Line numbers and column numbers tracked for error messages\n- Expects exact token sequences (e.g., `workflow <string> { ... }`)\n- Rejects conflicting `host` and `container` blocks\n- Rejects steps with multiple/no \"type-defining\" fields\n\n---\n\n### **8. Existing Validation Warnings & Errors**\n\n**Validation Error Examples** (from workflow.go):\n```go\n\"workflow %q: no entry step defined\"\n\"workflow %q: entry step %q not found\"\n\"workflow %q: step %q result %q is not wired\"\n\"workflow %q: step %q is orphaned (unreachable)\"\n\"workflow %q: collect references unknown step %q\"\n\"workflow %q: collect references undeclared result %q on step %q\"\n\"duplicate output mapping for env var %q targeting step %q\"\n```\n\n**Parse Errors** (from parser.go):\n```go\n\"line %d col %d: expected %v, got %v\"\n\"duplicate workflow name %q\"\n\"step %q has multiple of 'prompt', 'run', 'workflow_name'\"\n\"step %q has none of 'prompt', 'run', or 'workflow_name'\"\n\"workflow %q has both \\\"host\\\" and \\\"container\\\" blocks\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### **9. CLI Command Structure & Help**\n\n**Help Text Storage:**\n- All help in `/cmd/cloche/help.go`, `subcommandHelp` map\n- One entry per command: init, health, run, status, logs, poll, list, stop, delete, tasks, loop, get, set, workflow, project, shutdown\n- Format: Structured text with Usage, Flags, Examples, Environment sections\n\n**Command Categories:**\n\n**Non-daemon (local):**\n- `init` - Bootstrap project\n- `health` - Query daemon HTTP API for health\n- `get`/`set` - Read/write run context\n- `tasks` - Query task pipeline\n- `workflow` - List/visualize workflows\n- `project` - Show project info\n\n**Daemon-dependent (require gRPC):**\n- `run` - Launch workflow\n- `status` - Query run state\n- `logs` - Stream/display logs\n- `poll` - Wait for runs\n- `list` - List all runs\n- `stop` - Cancel run\n- `delete` - Remove container\n- `loop` - Control orchestration\n- `shutdown` - Stop daemon\n\n---\n\n### **10. Interfaces & Hexagonal Architecture** (internal/ports/)\n\n**Store Interface** (ports/store.go):\n- `RunStore` - Create/get/update/list runs\n- `CaptureStore` - Save/get step executions\n- `LogStore` - Persist log files\n- `EvolutionStore` - Track workflow evolution\n\n**Container Runtime Interface** (ports/container.go):\n- `ContainerRuntime` - Start/stop/inspect/copy Docker containers\n- `ImageEnsurer` - (optional) Validate/rebuild images\n\n**Agent Adapter Interface** (ports/agent.go):\n- `AgentAdapter` - Execute agent steps in container\n\n---\n\n### **11. Version Strategy**\n\n**File:** `/workspace/internal/version/VERSION` (single line, currently \"1.3.0\")\n\n**Format:** `major.minor.build` (semver)\n- **Build**: Increment on every compile/release\n- **Minor**: Backward-compatible features, API updates\n- **Major**: Backward-incompatible changes\n\n**Version Commands:**\n- `cloche -v` - Shows CLI, daemon, agent versions\n- Daemon: `GetVersion` gRPC endpoint\n- Agent: Docker run `cloche-agent -v`\n\n---\n\n### **Key Absolute File Paths for Reference:**\n\n- `/workspace/cmd/cloche/main.go` - CLI dispatcher (753 lines)\n- `/workspace/cmd/cloche/workflow.go` - Workflow listing/rendering (380 lines)\n- `/workspace/cmd/cloche/project.go` - Project info command (134 lines)\n- `/workspace/cmd/cloche/init.go` - Project scaffolding (283 lines)\n- `/workspace/cmd/cloche/help.go` - All help text (488 lines)\n- `/workspace/internal/domain/workflow.go` - Domain types & validation (301 lines)\n- `/workspace/internal/dsl/parser.go` - Workflow parser (616 lines)\n- `/workspace/internal/dsl/lexer.go` - Tokenizer (150+ lines)\n- `/workspace/internal/dsl/token.go` - Token type definitions (69 lines)\n- `/workspace/internal/config/config.go` - Config loading (119 lines)\n- `/workspace/internal/version/version.go` - Version embedding (15 lines)\n- `/workspace/internal/ports/store.go` - Data access interfaces\n- `/workspace/internal/ports/container.go` - Container runtime interface\n- `/workspace/internal/ports/agent.go` - Agent adapter interface\n- `/workspace/docs/workflows.md` - DSL documentation & examples\n\nThis comprehensive understanding covers CLI structure, workflow parsing, configuration, validation, project resolution, and all the interfaces that enable the hexagonal architecture."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ac4310c5ac652c299 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 73537\ntool_uses: 37\nduration_ms: 71134</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"955b2dd5-cc52-456b-afc0-0035f6eae0d8","uuid":"00b60ae5-7df6-4f42-83c0-9d9df82ea32e","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Explore the project structure to understand:\n1. How existing CLI commands are structured in cmd/cloche/ \n2. How workflow parsing works (the DSL parser)\n3. What config.toml looks like and how it's parsed\n4. The domain types for Workflow, Step, Result\n5. How the project directory / .cloche/ directory is resolved\n6. Any existing validation logic\n\nFocus on: cmd/cloche/, internal/domain/, any config parsing code, workflow parsing code. Be very thorough - read full files for the CLI command structure and workflow parser.","agentId":"ac4310c5ac652c299","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have all the information needed. Let me compile a comprehensive report.\n\n## Comprehensive Project Structure Exploration Report\n\nBased on thorough examination of the Cloche codebase, here's the complete understanding of the project structure and how it works:\n\n---\n\n### **1. CLI Command Structure** (cmd/cloche/)\n\n**Main.go dispatcher pattern:**\n- The CLI has a simple switch-based dispatcher in `main()` that routes commands into two categories:\n  1. **Non-daemon commands** (init, health, get, set, tasks, workflow, project) - execute locally or via HTTP\n  2. **Daemon commands** (run, status, logs, poll, list, stop, delete, loop, shutdown) - require gRPC connection\n\n- **Key entry points:**\n  - `cmdRun()` - Initiates workflow execution (lines 156-214)\n  - `cmdStatus()`, `cmdLogs()`, `cmdList()` - Query daemon state\n  - `cmdWorkflow()` - List/render workflows\n  - `cmdProject()` - Display project info\n  - `cmdInit()` - Bootstrap new project\n  - `cmdGet()` / `cmdSet()` - Run context store access\n\n- **Version handling:**\n  - Single version file at `/workspace/internal/version/VERSION` (currently \"1.3.0\")\n  - Embedded via `//go:embed` in `version/version.go`\n  - CLI shows version warnings if daemon/agent versions differ\n\n- **Command discovery:**\n  - All help text stored in `/cmd/cloche/help.go` in a `subcommandHelp` map\n  - Supports `cloche <cmd> --help`, `cloche help <cmd>`, and top-level `cloche --help`\n\n---\n\n### **2. Workflow DSL Parser** (internal/dsl/)\n\n**Parser Architecture:**\n- **Lexer** (`lexer.go`) - Tokenizes input into tokens (IDENT, STRING, INT, ARROW, etc.)\n- **Token types** (`token.go`) - 13 token types (LBRACE, RBRACE, LBRACKET, LBRACKET, ARROW, COLON, DOT, etc.)\n- **Parser** (`parser.go`, 616 lines) - Recursive descent parser that builds domain.Workflow objects\n\n**Key Parser Functions:**\n- `Parse(input string)` - Single workflow parse with optional location hint\n- `ParseAll(input string)` - Multiple workflows in one file (returns map[string]*domain.Workflow)\n- `ParseForHost(input string)` - Explicitly host location\n- `ParseAllForHost(input string)` - Multiple host workflows\n- `ParseForContainer(input string)` - Container location\n\n**DSL Grammar (from parser):**\n```\nworkflow \"<name>\" {\n  step <name> {\n    prompt = file(\"...\")   OR   run = \"...\"   OR   workflow_name = \"...\"\n    results = [result1, result2, ...]\n    <config-key> = <value>\n  }\n  \n  <step>:<result> -> <target-step> [output-mappings]\n  collect all|any(step:result, ...) -> target\n  \n  host { ... }     # marks as host workflow\n  container { ... } # container-specific config\n}\n```\n\n**Step Type Inference** (lines 268-297):\n- `prompt` field → agent step\n- `run` field → script step\n- `workflow_name` field → workflow step (host-only)\n- Must have exactly one; validation error otherwise\n\n**Wiring & Output Mappings** (parseWire, lines 446-482):\n- Format: `from:result -> to [KEY = output.path]`\n- Output paths support:\n  - `output` - raw output\n  - `output.field.nested` - JSON field access\n  - `output[0]` - array indexing\n  - Mixed: `output.items[0].name`\n\n**Collect Conditions** (parseCollect, lines 557-615):\n- Syntax: `collect all|any(step:result, ...) -> target`\n- Merges multiple results before wiring to next step\n\n---\n\n### **3. Domain Types** (internal/domain/workflow.go)\n\n**Core Types:**\n\n```go\ntype Workflow struct {\n  Name      string                // Workflow identifier\n  Location  WorkflowLocation      // host or container\n  Steps     map[string]*Step\n  Wiring    []Wire                // Graph edges\n  Collects  []Collect             // Multi-condition merges\n  EntryStep string                // First step to execute\n  Config    map[string]string     // Workflow-level config\n}\n\ntype Step struct {\n  Name    string\n  Type    StepType              // agent, script, workflow\n  Results []string              // Declared outcomes\n  Config  map[string]string     // Step-specific config\n}\n\ntype Wire struct {\n  From      string\n  Result    string\n  To        string\n  OutputMap []OutputMapping      // Env var mappings\n}\n\ntype OutputMapping struct {\n  EnvVar string\n  Path   OutputPath\n}\n\ntype Collect struct {\n  Mode       CollectMode           // all or any\n  Conditions []WireCondition\n  To         string\n}\n```\n\n**Workflow Location (lines 22-33):**\n- `LocationContainer` - default, runs in Docker\n- `LocationHost` - has `host { }` block, runs on daemon machine\n\n**WorkflowLocation vs StepType:**\n- Location determined by `host { }` block presence\n- Host workflows can have agent/script/workflow steps\n- Container workflows can only have agent/script steps\n- `ValidateLocation()` enforces this (lines 231-242)\n\n**Validation (lines 145-229):**\n- `Validate()` - Core validation (entry exists, all results wired, no orphans, output mappings unique)\n- `ValidateLocation()` - Rejects workflow_name in container workflows\n- `ValidateConfig()` - Warns about unrecognized config keys\n\n---\n\n### **4. Config Parsing** (internal/config/config.go)\n\n**Config File Location:**\n- Per-project: `<projectDir>/.cloche/config.toml`\n- Global: `~/.config/cloche/config` (optional)\n- Format: TOML using `github.com/BurntSushi/toml`\n\n**Config Structure:**\n```go\ntype Config struct {\n  Active        bool\n  Daemon        DaemonConfig        // listen, http, image, db, runtime, agent_path, llm_command\n  Evolution     EvolutionConfig     // enabled, debounce_seconds, min_confidence, max_prompt_bullets\n  Orchestration OrchestrationConfig // concurrency, stagger_seconds, list_tasks_command, dedup_seconds, stop_on_error\n}\n```\n\n**Load Function (line 57-74):**\n- Returns defaults if file missing\n- Merges file values with defaults()\n- Defaults: concurrency=1, stagger=1.0s, evolution enabled, debounce=30s\n\n**Default Template** (cmd/cloche/init.go, lines 73-82):\n- Created by `cloche init`\n- Sets `active = false` (must be manually enabled)\n\n---\n\n### **5. Project Directory & .cloche Resolution** (cmd/cloche/)\n\n**Current Working Directory Pattern:**\n- All commands use `os.Getwd()` to get project directory\n- Workflow loading: `projectDir + \"/.cloche/\" + name + \".cloche\"`\n- Glob discovery: `filepath.Glob(filepath.Join(clocheDir, \"*.cloche\"))`\n\n**Key Functions:**\n- `loadWorkflow(projectDir, name)` - Load single workflow by name (workflow.go, lines 119-141)\n- `discoverWorkflows(projectDir)` - Scan all `.cloche` files, parse workflows (lines 51-74)\n- `listWorkflows(projectDir)` - Group by location (container/host)\n- `showWorkflow(projectDir, name)` - Render ASCII graph\n\n**Path Resolution in cmdRun (lines 192-203):**\n```go\ncwd, _ := os.Getwd()\n// Try to load workflow to extract image config\nif wf, err := loadWorkflow(cwd, workflow); err == nil && wf.Location == domain.LocationContainer {\n  image = wf.Config[\"container.image\"]\n}\n// Send projectDir and image to daemon\nresp, err := client.RunWorkflow(ctx, &pb.RunWorkflowRequest{\n  ProjectDir: cwd,\n  Image:      image,\n  ...\n})\n```\n\n**Command Pattern:**\n- `cloche workflow` → lists all workflows\n- `cloche workflow <name>` → renders specific workflow graph\n- `cloche workflow <name> -p <dir>` → looks in alternate project directory\n\n---\n\n### **6. Workflow File Examples**\n\n**Container Workflow** (/workspace/develop.cloche):\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  step implement { prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\"); results = [success, fail] }\n  step test { run = \"go test ./...\"; results = [success, fail] }\n  \n  implemen